Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Traffic Accidents in Berlin 2019¶

This notebook follows a data analysis of a dataset including all traffic accidents recorded in Berlin for the year 2019. The explanations for the used codes can be found here: https://www.statistik-berlin-brandenburg.de/opendata/AfSBBB_BE_LOR_Strasse_Strassenverkehrsunfaelle_2019_Datensatzbeschreibung.pdf

#Coeff for correlation between 2 categorical columns.
def cramers_v(x, y):
    confusion_matrix = pd.crosstab(x,y)
    chi2 = ss.chi2_contingency(confusion_matrix)[0]
    n = confusion_matrix.sum().sum()
    phi2 = chi2/n
    r,k = confusion_matrix.shape
    phi2corr = max(0, phi2-((k-1)*(r-1))/(n-1))
    rcorr = r-((r-1)**2)/(n-1)
    kcorr = k-((k-1)**2)/(n-1)
    return np.sqrt(phi2corr/min((kcorr-1),(rcorr-1)))

# Custom correlation calculation in matrix form.
# Directly derived from panda's corr().
def custom_corr(df, func):   
    cols = df.columns
    idx = cols.copy()
    mat = df.to_numpy(na_value=np.nan, copy=False)
    mat = mat.T
    corrf = func
    K = len(cols)
    correl = np.empty((K, K), dtype=float)
    for i, ac in enumerate(mat):
        for j, bc in enumerate(mat):
            if i > j:
                continue

            if i == j:
                c = 1.0
            else:
                c = corrf(ac, bc)
            correl[i, j] = c
            correl[j, i] = c
    return pd.DataFrame(correl, index=idx,columns=cols)

print('Columns = Light conditions: 0 = Daylight , 1 = Dusk/Dawn , 2 = Darkness')
order = ['light', 'severe', 'deadly']
(pd.crosstab(data.UKATEGORIE, data.ULICHTVERH, normalize='index').mul(100)) \
    .loc[order] \
    .plot(kind='bar', stacked=True)
plt.title('Light Condiction vs Injury Level')
_ = plt.ylabel('%', fontsize=18)

Columns = Light conditions: 0 = Daylight , 1 = Dusk/Dawn , 2 = Darkness

Most accidents result in minor injuries, with a proportion of approx 85%, severe injuries around 15% and deadly accidents account for 0.2% of accidents.

For each injury category, most accidents happen during daytime, with only a few at dusk/dawn and at night, the ratio lies between 20% and 35%. I suppose, this effect is mostly due to the higher traffic amount during daytime and due to dusk/dawn only lasting for a small amount of time each day.

Notable is the increase in the proportion of deadly accidents from 20% during the day, to 35% at night. So although the traffic is probably much lower during the night, the chance of an accident being deadly increases significantly, pointing at the light conditions being a large factor in the severety of an accident.

# Count the occuring vehicle combinations.
df_comb = df.copy()
count_comb = []

# 2 involved vehicles
for comb in combinations(vehicles, 2):
    c = df_comb.loc[(df_comb[comb[0]] == 1) & 
                   (df_comb[comb[1]] == 1)
                   ].shape[0]
    count_comb.append((comb,c))
    
# 3 involved vehicles
for comb in combinations(vehicles, 3):
    c = df_comb.loc[(df_comb[comb[0]] == 1) & 
                   (df_comb[comb[1]] == 1) & 
                   (df_comb[comb[2]] == 1)
                   ].shape[0]
    count_comb.append((comb,c))
    
# 1 involved vehicle
for v in vehicles:
    others = set(vehicles).difference(set([v]))
    others = [others.pop() for i in range(len(others))]
    c = df_comb.loc[(df_comb[v]==1) & 
                   (df_comb[others[0]] == 0) &
                   (df_comb[others[1]] == 0) &
                   (df_comb[others[2]] == 0) &
                   (df_comb[others[3]] == 0) &
                   (df_comb[others[4]] == 0)
                   ].shape[0]
    count_comb.append((v,c))

If we take all accidents in a street and take the ratio of severe and deadly injuries to the total of accidents, the ratio can be interpreted as a meassure of severity or deadliness in that street.

In [37]:
f,ax = plt.subplots()
street_df = df.assign(count_str=lambda x: x.groupby(['STRASSE'], as_index=False)
    .OBJECTID.transform('count')) \
    .query('UKATEGORIE != \'light\' & count_str > 10') \
    .groupby(['BEZ','STRASSE'], as_index=False) \
    .agg(bad_inj=('UKATEGORIE', 'count'), 
         count_str=('count_str', 'first')) \
    .assign(ratio=lambda x: x['bad_inj'] / x['count_str'])

street_df.pipe((sns.regplot, 'data'),
              x='count_str',
              y='ratio',
              color=sns_c[0],
              fit_reg=True,
              scatter=True,
              scatter_kws={'edgecolor':'black'})
mean = street_df.ratio.mean()
ax.axhline(y=mean,color=sns_c[1],label='mean ratio',linestyle='--')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
Out[37]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fed9ee680f0>

Only streets with more than 10 accidents are used, to make sure that we ahave statistical significance of the ratio. Plotting all the street ratios shows a significant downward trend of ratios with growing accident count in the street, even below the overall mean, which means that mere regression to the mean is unlikely.

Doing the same analysis for each district respectively shows the districts that show this trend respectively.

Let's see how the street condiction affects the injury level of accidents. Most accidents happen in dry weather, which doesnt tell us much, because we are counting absolute numbers. Since most days are dry, most accidents will happen in dry weather.

To see how much the street condition is affecting injuries, we have to look at the proportion of the injury levels vs the street conditions. Interestingly, the rations are very constant, with the severe injury level even dropping slightly for snow/ice condition. Maybe due to people driving naturally slower.

Accidents types with the highest proportion of severe injury and death (level 2 & 3) are code 4, 6, 8 and 9. Those codes stand for:

4 = Head-on collision with oncoming vehicle

6 = Collision with vehicle and pedestrian

8 = Getting off the road to the RIGHT side

9 = Getting off the road to the LEFT side

The question arises again, if there are some vehicle types that are prone to a specific type of accident. To show these connection, I used a correlation heatmap, using cramers_v as correlation function:

Small correlations can be seen between Bikes and accident type 2, which stands for collision with driving/waiting vehicle in front, between bikes and pedestrians with type 5, which stands for collision with crossing/turning vehicle and the highest correlation is between pedestrian and type 6 which means collision with pedestrian involved (the correlation is obvious).
